Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was adopted as the 20th member of this European Space Agency as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the years it has participated in a number of projects of the Agency.
However, Poland’s journey to space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space flights before World War II; but they did not always encounter understanding.
For example, I recall the lecture by A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, which on December 6, 1933 represented ideas from his pioneering work Entering the cosmonautics.
The ideas of a young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cool, and after years, Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, he won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his entry into space science in France.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
In Polish journals he published hundreds of articles and wrote a number of books dedicated to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned cosmonautic promoter and his contribution was also appreciated by the fact that one of the craters on the reverse side of the moon was named by his name.
Already in 1925, a railway track was built in Poland, which was supposed to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown and neither the details of the project are known.
It is not clear whether the rocket was to be used for the launch of the drainage or for its braking.
Information about this sink is known only from the period press.
Since 1933, Polish artillery has begun to deal with rocket missiles.
The research was provided by the Chamber of Armament Techniques in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and Prof. Gustaw Mokrrzyckigi.
From preserved materials, it is clear that research has reached the stage of practical testing.
However, at the arrival of the German troops, the research was interrupted.
In 1937, a draft of a photoelectric fighter missile was introduced in the professional press, designed by the engineer Rohoziński and the following year, the work of the Missile was published - an air-torpeda and a rocketbomb of the author Lilni-Krzywoblocky.
Both projects were designed for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all the projects of military use of missile technology were devoted to the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Temporary Advisory Committee) which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities ended the beginning of the war.
Other works devoted to cosmonautics appear after the war in the Polish press thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautic Society (Polish Astronautic Society).
For the first time there is a mention of the company in the November issue of the 1954 magazine Problems, in which four more comprehensive articles are devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from Prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was clear that space research was a perspective field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) has been seeking entry into the International Astronautic Federation (founded 1951) and has already become an ordinary member of PTA in autumn.
And in the following year, the first chairman of PTA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959) became the vice-chairman of the International Astronautic Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has significantly contributed to the development of the very successful meteorological missile RM (Metrological Missile), which became the first Polish rocket to be carried out by scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The 1800-metre-access rocket was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of RM-1A was later built and in the summer of 1959, two-stage RM-2 rockets were launched in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
Another developmental type was already to be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 missile was supposed to have access to up to 14.5 km, and its task was to monitor the high wind.
However, in 1962, further developments were suspended.
The first RM-type rocket was developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was conceived as two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (named Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, differing in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
In the Meteor-1A rocket, space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C of 0.62 litres was available.
Maximum access for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aeronautical Institute was developing the Meteor-2 rocket, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to carry a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The meteor-2H and meteor-3 versions were built.
It is still necessary to mention the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the National Committee COSPAR two years later.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Interkosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimír Remk.
