Szabo: “Germany must play a bigger role”
Germany abstained from voting in decision-making on the adoption of Palestine.
According to the U.S.-Europe relations expert Stephen Szabo, Berlin is balancing on the narrow edge of diplomacy.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first signaled that it would vote against a proposal for the observer status of Palestinians in the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Shabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
But now Germany must be cautious about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I don’t think it will support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the Libya Uprising in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
This was the end of NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance on serious international issues?
Yes, it is.
The reason for this is that it is changing its foreign policy from a policy that was so-called US-led to German foreign policy.
The situation is more difficult for Europeans to have no coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are between the two fronts.
They are expected to play an independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think that they are still living in their role, but they are on their way to a more “normal” foreign policy.
The foreign policy they have in France or the UK.
What exactly does “normal” foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the readiness to be interested in the case of national interests and attitudes that are independent of the positions of the US or European partners.
I think that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. by exports and its relations with certain areas, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
The economic interests of Germany are to some extent different from the economic interests of other powers, and therefore Germany must protect its interests.
Did economic interests affect attitudes in the Middle East conflict and vote in the United Nations?
First, Germany has a large outlet in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf States.
Therefore, it must be careful not to scare the public, but neither elites in the Arab countries.
Anyway, it plays a role.
But I would not like to attribute too much importance to this, it is not a completely unilateral relationship.
However, this plays an important role in German considerations.
Did Germany’s relations with the United States damage when Germany abstained from voting in the case of both important decisions, for example when voting on Palestine?
I think that in Europe and even in the U.S. there is a great understanding of the German stance.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic a bad thing as it was in Libya.
Perhaps Germany will even benefit from some respect.
This indicates that it must be considered an international player and that its interests must be taken into account.
There are different views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
The United States, on the other hand, has clearly spoken for the veto.
Are there differences between the United States and many European nations?
These differences have always existed as a result of U.S. internal policy.
I think Obama’s government probably has a significant understanding of European attitude.
But as a result of the political situation there, of course, this position cannot be held public.
I think that differences in opinions are not as big as they always seem.
When you look at the relations between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, Obama is not very excited about Netanyahu’s policy at all.
Is it not difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand and with the position of the most important partners in the EU on the other?
I think that’s what makes it difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a bit easier for Germany if there were a coherent and united European policy, which is currently not happening.
Therefore, they cannot be part of a wider line and must instead drive things forward from their own position.
This is what they do with the euro.
I believe that Germany will take on a leading role in the future and push Europe towards a European stance.
This is not easy for Germany, of course, because of the relationship with Israel.
That was always a sensitive topic.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they have to play an independent role.
Does Germany see itself as a major international player? Do they want to take on the lead?
Or is it still difficult for Germany to lead?
Germany is still not used to this, it is still unpleasant, and for obvious reasons it is still difficult to play a role.
For example, if we look at the European crisis, every time Germany takes on a bigger role, there will be anti-German sentiments.
This does not make it easier for the Germans.
It’s actually an old problem: we don’t want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the US.
It must be acceptable for various neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The impact of the US on European politics is now constantly falling, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment.
The Germans will have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don’t like it, they feel uncomfortable and make it even more unpopular - c’est la knows!
Stephen Szabo is a representative of the Director of Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly study the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
